day while it questions the make-up of the fantasies and the capitalistic conditions of the play involved. Arguing that part of the appeal of such dream worlds is the polymorphous perversity with which they scramble identity and character, the author traces the postindustrial milieux from which such fantasies have arisen in postwar Japan and been popularly received in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnimated filmsxJapan. 0aAnimated filmszJapan. 0aConsumer goodsxJapan. 0aConsumer goodszJapan. 0aGamesxJapan. 0aGameszJapan. 0aPhilosophy, Japanese. 0aToy industryxJapan. 0aToy industryzJapan. 0aToysxJapan. 0aToysxMarketingxJapan. 0aToyszJapanxMarketing. 0aToyszJapan. 0aVideo gamesxJapan. 0aVideo gameszJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938991423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520938991.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles